Sure, I'd be happy to help with that! Here's a C# code snippet implementing a K-Nearest Neighbors algorithm for the Iris dataset:
```
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.IO;
using System.Linq;
class Program
{
 static void Main()
 {
 // Load the Iris dataset
 var lines = File.ReadAllLines("iris.csv").Skip(1);
 var data = lines.Select(line => line.Split(','))
 .Select(tokens => new
 {
 SepalLength = double.Parse(tokens[0]),
 SepalWidth = double.Parse(tokens[1]),
 PetalLength = double.Parse(tokens[2]),
 PetalWidth = double.Parse(tokens[3]),
 Species = tokens[4]
 })
 .ToArray();
 // Define a test data point
 var test = new
 {
 SepalLength = 5.1,
 SepalWidth = 3.5,
 PetalLength = 1.4,
 PetalWidth = 0.2
 };
 // Compute the distances between the test data point and each data point in the dataset
 var distances = data.Select(d => new
 {
 Distance = Math.Sqrt(Math.Pow(d.SepalLength - test.SepalLength, 2) +
 Math.Pow(d.SepalWidth - test.SepalWidth, 2) +
 Math.Pow(d.PetalLength - test.PetalLength, 2) +
 Math.Pow(d.PetalWidth - test.PetalWidth, 2)),
 Species = d.Species
 })
 .OrderBy(d => d.Distance)
 .ToArray();
 // Select the K nearest neighbors
 var k = 5;
 var neighbors = distances.Take(k)
 .ToArray();
 // Classify the test data point based on the majority vote of the K nearest neighbors
 var majority = neighbors.GroupBy(n => n.Species)
 .OrderByDescending(g => g.Count())
 .First()
 .Key;
 Console.WriteLine($"The test data point is classified as {majority}.");
 }
}
```
Explanation:
The K-Nearest Neighbors algorithm is a machine learning algorithm that can be used for classification or regression. It works by finding the K nearest data points to a test data point in a dataset, and then classifying the test data point based on the majority vote of the K nearest neighbors.
In this code snippet, we first load the Iris dataset from a CSV file. We then define a test data point with four features: SepalLength, SepalWidth, PetalLength, and PetalWidth. Next, we compute the distances between the test data point and each data point in the dataset using the Euclidean distance formula. We then select the K nearest neighbors, which in this case is set to 5. Finally, we classify the test data point based on the majority vote of the K nearest neighbors.
Note that this code snippet assumes that the Iris dataset is stored in a file called "iris.csv", and that the first line of the file contains headers. The dataset should have 150 rows and 5 columns, where the first four columns are the features and the last column is the target variable (i.e., the species of the iris).

