Your code looks correct and will output the least number of coins the man needs to pay for the items. However, there is a more efficient way to solve this problem using dynamic programming. 
You can create an array of size 7 (the sum of all possible item costs) and initialize it with a value of 4 (the maximum number of coins the man can have). Then, iterate through the coins and subtract their value from the array at the corresponding index. Finally, return the minimum value in the array.
Here's the code for the dynamic programming solution:
```
package main
import "fmt"
func main() {
 coins := []int{1, 2, 3}
 items := []int{1, 2, 3}
 dp := make([]int, 7)
 for i := range dp {
 dp[i] = 4
 }
 dp[0] = 0
 for _, coin := range coins {
 for i := coin; i <= 6; i++ {
 dp[i] = min(dp[i], dp[i-coin]+1)
 }
 }
 totalCost := items[0] + items[1] + items[2]
 fmt.Printf("The man needs at least %v coins to pay for the items.", dp[totalCost])
}
func min(a, b int) int {
 if a < b {
 return a
 }
 return b
}
```
This solution has a time complexity of O(n^2) and a space complexity of O(n), where n is the sum of all possible item costs.

